body:
When I click or arrow-key on a closing character (like a parentheses or brace or bracket), if the cursor is on the _right_ side of the character, it highlights that character (and its opening character) but only if there is not another closing character right after it... at that point it will only highlight the closing character if the cursor is on the _left_ side of that character.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32692076/40459939-79102128-5ec1-11e8-8102-db0d25e804f6.png)

The problems with this are getting possibly misguided indications of opening character, and cumulatively a lot of extra keypresses/clicking.

Versions:
<!-- Use Help > Report Issue to prefill these. -->
- VSCode Version: 1.23.1
- OS Version: Windows, Mac, Linux

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Make some code like this:
```
jQuery.SomeFunction = function () {
    $.ajax({
        url: 'some.url'
    })    
    .done(function (data) {
        // do whatever
    })
    .fail(function (data) {
        // do other things
    });
}
```
2. Click on the right side of a closing paren, then click or arrow-key to the left of the closing brace.
3. Notice even Notepad++ does it correctly:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/32692076/40460053-1ba70b72-5ec2-11e8-8887-855cb612c577.png)

<!-- Launch with `code --disable-extensions` to check. -->
Does this issue occur when all extensions are disabled?: Yes

## Issue Type

Feature Request / Question

## Description

Hi,
Maybe this is already possible, but I didn't spot anything in the docs
within a Multi-root Workspace where you have a .code-workspace file like the below with multiple folders listed

is there a variable for the top level directory where the .code-workspace lives?
${workspaceFolder} equals the path of the folder which changes from folder to folder
in the below example ${workspaceFolder}/../ works fine for most folders, but not the Root one which is one directory up

Having a common set of settings for for all folders where there are file paths are involved at different levels makes things difficult if your trying to create a path that's relative to the location of the .code-workspace file

If there was a variable that represented the top level directory ./ (Root where the .code-workspace file lives)
this would make life a bit easier when referencing things like virtual environments within python

Another way around this is if there was such a thing as custom variables, since you can reference a setting via
${config:Name} but not create a custom setting for use later on in a path setting.

